      <prefercite id="aspace_090e79358098f5c0d948ea5cfb2b112f">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Nathanael Greene Papers. Manuscripts and Archives, Yale University Library.</p>  
      </prefercite>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_e6a54a72c9ea73aa1885507576c177c1">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>This small but important collection of Nathanael Greene papers consists of thirty-one original letters, one photostatic copy, and two volumes of typed transcripts of letters exchanged by Greene and Revolutionary War officers, government officials, family members, and others between 1774 and 1793. There is also a volume of typed transcripts of Revolutionary War era documents containing letters by George Washington, Nathan Hale, William Hooper, and others, the roll of minute-men of Bridgewater, Massachusetts, military commissions, and so forth. The volumes of transcripts are copies of original documents and letters formerly owned by William A. Read and now in Clements Library of the University of Michigan. The volumes and the thirty-one original letters were given to Yale University by Duncan Read in 1967.</p>
         <p>The Greene papers are of great value to students of the American Revolution and for those interested in Greene's life.</p>
         <p>Further correspondence of Nathanael Greene can be found in the Bernhard Knollenberg Collection, Manuscript Group Number 26.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
